segments.text: who has been at Texas A&M since 1973 and is in the Department of Educational Administration and is going to share a few ideas or thoughts about changes that have occurred at Texas A&M since 1973 or since you arrived.
And can you tell me from your perception or your vantage point what have been some of the major
changes that have impacted the university or the College of Education?
Well, the impact of the College of Ed, of course, is we've had a change in the dean, the dean's office and the department head office.
When I came there in 73, of course, Frank Hubert was the dean.
And now Dean Corrigan is the dean.
And Harold Hawkins was the department head.
And now Dave Earleson's the department head as far as
Administratively, those have been significant changes, and then from the standpoint of enrollment, size of faculty.
When I came there, there were four professors in the department, and now there are 11 full-time tenured faculty or tenure-track faculty.
We admitted an average of 22 doctoral students and master's students a year, and now we admit somewhere around 60 a year.
In the last two years alone, we've admitted 86 doctoral students in just two years, and from 1975 to 81, we only admitted 122 graduate students total.
into the program.
So our numbers have grown significantly.
What are you attributing all of this to?

Well, the growth of the university is probably based on the need for master's and particularly doctoral degrees in public school administration to move up into the top leadership positions in this state.
Used to be a master's degree in certification would make you eligible for the top
level positions, and now it's the PhD or the EDD is required to get in line to be eligible to secure the positions.
Okay.

Because you've mentioned the two leaderships in the college and in the department, how has the leadership in both of those affected the climate or the culture of the number one, the department, being that that was a change, or the college?
Well,
Frank Hubert, you know, and his, you might say, autocratic administrative leadership style, he literally caught all the shots for the college and for the departments.

I sat in an admissions meeting with Frank where he'd literally have the whole pile of candidates in front of him, and he'd go through and say, accept, deny, accept, deny, and when he got done with that process, he'd tell the faculty on
And that's the way our admissions were ran.
I mean, Frank literally selected who he wanted into the admin department.
And where when Dean Corrigan came in, of course, he turned over to Hawkins, total control of the department.
And at that point, the faculty selected the candidates.
And of course, David Erlandson, who came in after Hawkins,
He's a very democratic leader, and we as a total faculty make all the decisions on policy and key decisions as it relates to curriculum, employment of our faculty.
Again, one to Frank Hubert's era, you'd go up and interview with Frank, and he either hired you or he didn't.
The department head was merely a personnel director that lined up the final interview.
And now with Dean Corrigan,
There the department makes a decision and the recommendation goes to the dean and in eight years he's been there.
I've never known him to deny the request of the faculty for any new faculty member that we wanted nor ever got involved with the admissions process.
Dean Corgan's never sat in on one admissions meeting in all the years he's been dean of our college.
And when Frank Hubert was here, we never had an admissions meeting unless Frank was going to be there.
So those, you know, as related to students, he's selected.
His criteria was 99% GRE.
And under Dean Corrigan, we select our own students.
And we have seven different variables, including GRE as one of the seven for admissions.
So it's a much more flexible, open, realistic admissions process.
And that's directly attributed to the two different drastic styles.

of leadership in the dean's office and to some extent a change in leadership style from the department because harold hawkins pretty much followed the dean's lead as far as being an autocratic leader he didn't delegate or turn loose much power and authority to the faculty where david delegates almost everything to the faculty where possible and so the climate of the organizations
probably had 180 degree change in the two administrations.
Was it hard to adjust to not having a lot of input to having so much input?
Do people handle that pretty well?
Well, in that admin department, where all of us who are in the department

have come there with a tremendous amount of administrative experience and were used to calling the shots in organizations or having a leadership style which we insisted that our subordinates share in the decision-making process.
No, it was very easy for us.
It was very refreshing.
It was a sigh of relief that now we had control.
of the department and in essence we're going to be successful or fail based on our own input knowledge and awareness of how we could run that department and many of us ran
far bigger faculties and staffs professionally before we got to the university than any of us collectively ever had to participate in such a small department of 8, 9, 10, 11 faculty members.
And none of us were really used to working for a superordinate like Frank Huber who totally, you know, was an autocratic leader and made all the decisions for us.

We resented it as a faculty, and some of that resentment was so obvious that some of the early faculty members did not get tenure and were forced to leave because, quite frankly, Dean Huber didn't like them.
So he got rid of them.
He just didn't put them on tenure, and so they had to leave.
So he made all the tenure decisions as well.
Oh, absolutely.
Frank, if Frank didn't like you, you were in big trouble.
You just didn't stay around very long.
And if Frank liked you or if he perceived you were doing your job, you didn't have any problems with him.
I personally never had a problem with him from the moment he hired me.
until the day he retired.
I never had a bad word with him and got along with him well.

But I was such a junior faculty, working on soft money, he had no reason, he and I had no reason to cross and all the things he heard about what the department was doing and the area I was responsible for was all positive, so he had no reason to get upset with what I was doing as an individual.
OK, now the college, like you said, has changed somewhat in the climate and the culture because of the two drastic changes.
However, the mission has remained pretty much the same, the teaching, the research, and the service, which is in conjunction with the mission of a land-grant university.
To what extent do you feel that the college is achieving its mission?
And in what proportion, maybe, of the teaching, research?
Because I think it has shifted somewhat.
maybe even within the two administrations?
Yeah, I think teaching is obviously the number one area that is getting the most attention now at the university.

I think back in the earlier year, particularly under Dean Hubert, with the faculty as small as it was, at least in the admin department, and I think to a great extent the other departments, there was a lot
off-campus offerings throughout the state, Temple, Belton, Killeen, Houston, the Valley, San Angelo, the Beaumont area.
A lot of courses were taken off campus to serve the needs of students through the extension program.
And the last few years, you know, most of those programs have dried up.
The university has

has more went into a teaching research posture, where teaching primarily on the main campus and emphasizing research and now service to the field is just a secondary or byproduct of the College of Education.
We used to go down, several departments would go down to Houston and for two years we did the certification on-site for all of HISD's central office administrators.
We used to teach in Austin and train their administrators in the central office.
We literally had a network of off-campus sites all over the state of Texas.

and now the only off-campus center we maintain is here in San Antonio and we are the only department in the college other than IDED that is doing any type of off-campus teaching and all the other departments have come back into the university and are very content
to have the students come to the campus to get the instruction and are not willing to send their faculty off-campus anymore to do the off-campus.
So is it de-emphasizing the service part of it?
However, this department is perceived by a lot of the other departments as being very service-oriented.
So does everybody feel that
Service is the emphasis of the department versus research, specifically research, because there seems to be.
If the faculty was honest, they'd say we're probably 40% teaching, 40% service, and about 20% research.

in reality because with the principal center that's certainly a service center entity the community ed center the higher ed center now that stan carpenter's developed in the process of developing the ucea connection we had with editing through phil west etc that was a lot of service oriented type of activities then the heavy numbers of
in excess of 200 full-time doctoral enrollments in the department now.
Those two things probably occupy about 80% of our time, and then there's 20%
research.
I don't see that much individual faculty research going on that is not directly connected with dissertation research.

I think, now if you take into consideration dissertation research, that percentage might go up, but when I think of research at universities, I think of faculty members going out on their own doing some creative experimental research by themselves and then writing that up and that making a contribution.
I don't see our faculty in our department doing that much independent research.
Does the faculty get any pressure from the administration to increase research activity and decrease service, or do they?
If it is, I haven't been aware of it, no.
I think that our dean is satisfied that we are making an impact in the state by the service
that we are rendering through the different programs within the department.
And he knows we're finishing larger than usual records of studies and dissertations that he hasn't really put any pressure on the department or any of the faculty members, as I'm aware of.
Does that affect the tenure?
Anything on your evaluation for tenure?
I don't think so.
I think if you're

teaching your load, providing some external services to the field, taking care of your students and maintaining your office hours, publishing occasional journal articles based on research of your students or some independent research that you conduct as a faculty member.
We've never had that pressure.
Oh, thank you.
Very good.
We appreciate that.
What did you do, run?
Thank you.
OK. Now, has the tremendous growth that you talked about earlier affected how you were able to work with students?
And the growth has been more in the undergraduate, but you expressed it's also grown tremendously in your department.
How has that affected your ability to work with students like you'd like on a one-on-one?
I think that I spend probably 80% of my time working with students.
Last year, I finished 16 PhDs and ADDs.
I chaired eight of those, and I sat on eight more.
And with the San Antonio program here, I probably
and responsible for somewhere from 25 to 40% of all the new admissions that come into the department.
I recruit them and bring them in for the department.
So I spend about 80% of my time on taking care of students and teaching in the off-campus setting.
And by the nature of my research course, I'm still actively involved with students developing their proposals.
So I'm extremely busy, but I don't think anyone's being neglected.
because of the large numbers we deal with.

I choose to work with students and spend a lot of time taking care of their needs, and this may be an excuse why I don't publish as much as probably some people would like me to, but it hadn't affected me.
Can you share some ideas of what your perceptions are of the collaboration among departments within the college, or maybe even collaboration within other colleges,

Probably during the last three or four years, and I directly attribute this to Dean Corrigan's administration and leadership style encouragement for it to happen, I've seen a tremendous amount of cooperation between the
departments.

An example of that is the instructional management certificate between EDCI and Ed Admin where we jointly collaborate with about an 86 to 90 hour doctoral program and we really don't care where the student gets the degree in EDCI or Ed Ad.
They take almost an equal amount of hours

Four or five years ago that wasn't even conceivable, let alone possible, because of the structure of the departments and the rigidity of the administration that kept us all pretty well turfed to our own areas and we didn't integrate or have an interdisciplinary approach.
With Dean Corrigan, we have a lot of interaction now with the

various departments, the pro-seminars that were developed in 78, 79 through the Record of Study program, you might say had forced integration potential where it required the six departments to work together in providing the pro-seminar experience, and that was really the beginning
for this working cooperative.
And then as we got to be more familiar with each other as faculty members and as disciplines, more collaborative interaction, you know, occurred.
And now we've got lots of interactions with various departments, mainly within the college, but over with Mildred Fox Shop and I, industrial engineering,
That's another example.
We've done a lot of work with them over the last five or six years.
And so I think it's been positive.
It's going on.
It continues to grow.
And we now have a mentality of an interdisciplinary approach to educating doctoral students rather than a departmental approach to educating doctoral students.
Who was the name that you mentioned in industrial ed?
No, industrial engineering.
I'm sorry.
It's Mildren Fox.
Mildren, M-I-L-D-R-E-N?
Mm-hmm.
And he teaches the collective bargaining, arbitration, and the public and private sector.
It's a 10-hour block that deals with the whole domain of arbitration, collective bargaining, negotiation.
And ed-ac students have to take that?
It's a support field for a minor,

for ed-ad majors and we have a large number of our majors do elect to take the i engineering support field because of its implication for unions and grievances and collective bargaining and that whole nine yards of

which is just for the, not so much for the educator here in the south, but you know, Shanker supposedly five or six years ago said Texas was going to be the next area that they tried to get involved with unions.

Well, it really hasn't happened, but the material that Fox covers in there is of such interest to the administrators, and I think it helps them work with negotiating contracts, working with school boards to negotiate contracts with teachers, and it's still a beneficial support field.
Okay, the next question has to do with your perceptions of how outsiders view the College of Education at A&M.
Do you have a feel for that since you do some traveling?
Yeah, I think, again, in the early years, you've got to understand the college was formed in 1969.
I got there in 73.
We were an unknown entity probably up through, even through the 70s.
I think around 1980 and beyond, and certainly in the last three or four years,

with the leadership of Dean Corrigan, the fact that he was selected as the only dean on the select committee to work with Ross Perot, and that got so much press with House Bill 72 and the involvement of our college and the certification, the training of administrators.

and the numbers that we're training and producing on an annual basis I think has moved us to the forefront in the eyes of many of the educators across this state that we are now the college of education in the state that probably has the best
overall delivery of doctoral certification and master's students in education and I think that's probably a complete turnaround from when I came here in 73 to what it is today.
Okay how about maybe a vision of what you feel that that's facing and the college appears to be at a crossroads because of the undergraduate program being drastically
affected with these new changes, how do you see the future of the College of Education at this point?
It's hard to say what the impact of 994 is going to be on the teacher education part of the College of Ed.
I think from the standpoint of the Ed Psych Department, from the Ed Admin Department, the IDED Department, particularly... All the non-teachers.
Yeah, the non-teaching areas.
We're

We're only going to increase in numbers of quality and quantity of students with I think you'll see more of an emphasis on minority recruitment and actually completion, retention and completion of those students through our program.
I see the quality of the program continuing to get better and better.
the opportunity for a minority to become faculty members with our department, which will add another dimension to deal with this increased population of administrators that we'll be dealing with.
And I just see things getting more quality, a better program, perhaps a little bit more emphasis on urban education
because of the strong need for urban school administrators and so many of our urban school districts so highly inundated with minority populations, both black and Hispanic.
I think we may change our emphasis to more of an urban curriculum than a rural curriculum.
Most of our doctoral students are coming from the larger urban areas.
And that's where they need
tend to need that terminal degree to sustain those upward mobility and to keep the top administrative positions.
In the rural areas, certification and just some years of experience seem to be enough education.
But as we get into the urban setting and the big suburbans around these urban school districts, the doctorate's almost mandatory.
And I think that's where we're going to see the change.
Well, and the fact, too, that you have brought it

part of the campus to San Antonio, for example, has increased that or has helped that considerably because it has made it at least a feasible possibility for the people that have to work full-time and cannot possibly move over there full-time.
Right, and I think that the market here in San Antonio, of course, will only increase for us as we are capable of handling larger numbers of
doctoral students myself in a few short years.
I've been down here and probably have 30 or 40 in the process now, and probably 60% of those are minority.
There you are.
But you don't necessarily recruit the minorities.
It's just the way it happens, or are you aggressively pursuing the minority recruitment?
I probably more aggressively recruit minority if I feel by reviewing their

transcripts and interviewing them one-on-one, that they really have the ability, the interest to pursue a doctorate, I probably try to encourage them that they can do it and that I'll help them more so than I would
maybe some non-minority students, just because the numbers of those folks are always out there.

And the fact, too, that we draw those in, other faculty members draw those in from other parts of the state, and I think one of the advantages of me being down here, and purposes, quite frankly, is to...

to increase the minority pool in the university and department and to get these folks in the programs and to graduate them, get them back out in these top leadership positions, which we've already demonstrated we can do and we have done.
So I think it's worth it.
OK. Do you have something that stands out in your mind as a highlight of the time, the years that you have spent at Texas A&M, or maybe a contribution?
And we've already touched on a lot of the contributions you've made by the recruiting
traveling to San Antonio weekly to teach and so forth.
But is there something, an insight, or something that stands out?
Well, probably for me, it's been the opportunity to work with the community education movement in the state.
And the fact when I came here, there were six school districts that had community education.
And today, there are in excess of over 100 school districts.
And I more or less had...
input on almost all of those coming into being, and particularly in the San Antonio, Austin, and the Rio Grande area, which comprises probably 50% of all the community ed projects in the state.
You know, I personally started all those projects, trained the directors, and served as their consultant for many years that

that we've been in existence and to have that opportunity to go out and then stand back eight, ten years later and look at a place like Austin that's got 29,000 non-duplicated enrollments in their community at evening classes, over 100,000 participants.
Then you come down the road to Comal, New Bronzeville and look at the success of those programs and you move into the San Antonio area where we originally got the SAISD

involved, which led us to Northeast, and now Northside is developing an excellent community ed model, and from Edgewood and East Central, South Sand, Harlandale, you know, it's gratifying to me to see the fruits of my labor

that was availed to me by the fact that I was at a major university that had a grant from a private foundation that gave me the latitude and freedom to go out and work in these school districts and try out some ideas and they were embraced by what I call futuristic leaders who saw the potential and now we have quite a strong community education network in what I call the I-35 syndrome from Dallas-Fort Worth all the way down through San Antonio and that's probably the highlight of my career.
I think
A lot of people could have come in and developed the off-campus program in San Antonio because there was such a need for it.
And the availability of a university like A&M to want to do off-campus work, that in itself I don't think is that unique.
But the ability, I think, with my 21 years in community ed to help start so many of these 100 school districts that I personally was the original contact

the trainer, the follow-up consultant to these projects, and then see them sustain themselves far beyond after I left or had any influence at all on the success of those programs, that's probably the high spot for me.
Well, now that that soft money has sort of dwindled, what do you see happening?
Because community ed has picked up momentum in a lot of places, and it's almost, like they said, something whose time has come now, and it's coming of age.
What is happening, and
I know the center is still at Texas A&M and probably will continue there because it is getting support from the university.
Do you perceive any changes there?

I think when we only saw about nine or ten of the districts folding when the soft money this year finally ended is a strong indication that we've hit upon a philosophy or an idea that once implanted in a local school district's

leadership style or philosophy of education is very difficult to remove from the system, that I think community education as we have developed it here will be around for many, many years in the future.
I'm concerned about the expansion of projects so that new school districts will

some outside influence of either state funding again for pilot projects or private foundation money but as far as sustaining the network of approximately 100 school districts between now and the year 2000 I think in 10-12 years from now we'll probably have 80% of what we're working with right now will still be in place but yet that only represents about 10% of school districts in the state and if we don't get some outside

support from either legislature or from some private foundation like we had in the early years of the development of Community Ed in Texas, I don't think we'll see any growth and I think that'll be regrettable.

Our growth may be in the standpoint of occasionally adding new projects, but I think those new projects will be added by former graduate students of our program who take the Community Ed curriculum or courses and believe in it as a leadership style, implement the program as part of their

offerings to a local school district in turn for hiring them and that'll probably just maintain what we lose of those districts that have a change in administration of boards or superintendent and decide not to fund again and we'll maybe pick up those numbers by new young administrators coming in and developing but I don't think

in the next five to ten years if we don't have any influence of state legislation or some priority by the state board that will give some incentives to local school districts to expand their use of public schools and go into the... Do you think the elected state board will have any impact?
Will it change attitudes in any way?
Because the support has not been there legislatively recently, or at least not as much as it's needed, right?
It's hard to say.
